4. Kaggle Integration Strategy

Kaggle plays a dual role in this project: as a training data source and as a competitive benchmarking platform. Both roles are critical to achieving the ML quality targets and academic credibility of the project.

4.1 Role 1 — Dataset Source
•Primary dataset: Google Play store reviews scraped locally via google-play-scraper
•Augmentation datasets: publicly available Kaggle datasets provide additional labelled training examples:
◦yelp-review-polarity — 598k labelled restaurant reviews for transfer pre-training
◦amazon-reviews-for-sentiment-analysis — 3.6M product reviews, filtered to app categories
◦app-reviews — 6k pre-labelled mobile app reviews from Kaggle, directly relevant to project domain
•All Kaggle datasets are downloaded via the Kaggle Python API: kaggle datasets download <dataset-slug>

4.2 Role 2 — Competition Participation
Participation in the following Kaggle competitions directly benchmarks model quality and improves leaderboard-validated F1 scores:
Competition	Relevance	Target Metric	Timeline
NLP Getting Started (Disaster Tweets)	Binary text classification with BERT; foundational for the fine-tuning pipeline	F1 Score	Phase 1
Yelp / Amazon Review Sentiment	2-class sentiment on user reviews — closest to Tinder review domain	Accuracy	Phase 2
Feedback Prize (NLP)	Multi-label NLP; tests aspect extraction techniques applicable to ABSA module	Macro F1	Phase 3
Google QUEST Q&A Labelling	Demonstrates ranking & relevance scoring transferable to keyword insights ranking	Spearman ρ	Optional

Kaggle Workflow
1.Set up Kaggle API credentials: kaggle.json → ~/.kaggle/kaggle.json (chmod 600)
2.Join competition via API: kaggle competitions list -s sentiment
3.Download data: kaggle competitions download -c <competition-name>
4.Train in Kaggle Notebook (GPU): commit notebook → Kaggle auto-saves + enables submission
5.Submit predictions: kaggle competitions submit -c <comp> -f submission.csv -m 'BERT v2'
6.Check leaderboard: kaggle competitions leaderboard <comp> --show
7.Port winning model weights back to the Sentix project fine-tuning pipeline

4.3 GPU Resource Strategy
Platform	Free GPU	Usage in Project
Kaggle Notebooks	30 hrs/week T4 / P100	Primary BERT fine-tuning environment; submit competition predictions
Google Colab (free)	T4, session-limited	Overflow training when Kaggle quota exhausted
Google Colab Pro	A100 / V100	Optional paid tier for large-batch RoBERTa fine-tuning
Local CPU	None	DistilBERT inference only (fast enough at < 200ms); all training offloaded



